deck_excerpt: Fiendsmith Snake-Eyes Post The Infinite Forbidden
Voiceless Voice Deck Featuring Branded Package and new Top Hat Hare the Silhoutte Magician and Silhouhatte from INFO.
deck_description:
Voiceless Voice Deck featuring the Branded engine as a mechanism to send Lo or Saphira from deck to GY as a way to access the former or setup the latter without playing into Droll and Lock Bird while potentially baiting out interuption.  The new Top Hat Hare the Silhoutte Magician and Silhouhatte are an extra back up line in case i get interupted and can't continue to play, but have 2 pieces of material, or i have a hand with a surplus of material that doesn't need to make Dyna Mondo for some reason or can make it in addition.  Otherwise the deck is what you'd expect, being at 46 is a bit higher than i prefer, but there isn't much to drop that significantly moves the needle without dropping the branded package which is ultimately a net loss in consistency and flexibility.  Pendulumgraph in the side is actually an interesting case, there are situations where you do want to side out the branded package for more non-engine, which presents a numbers problem, since thats 4 cards.  Normally this would mean adding a 1 of that will probably not be drawn, but since most VV cards, either directly or indirectly through other cards they access, can get to Pendulumgraph it can be sided over the Albaz without having this issue.  It helps Meteorburst does have applications in general, especially since it just ruins a lot of what Tenpai wants to do by negating Kaimen or Summoning and cheating Meteorburst who just turns off all their monsters, while Sauravis prevents them making Black Rose successfully.

For the love of god, do not tell someone Meteorburst can bring Pendulumgraph out of the scale for a second negate when you do this.  Meteorburst is an optional WHEN, Pendulumgraph summons, then moves, likely on purpose to prevent this interaction and to disallow Vortex Dragon's Bounce.  I've seen this claim made on multiple occasions that you can do this, you can't.

deck_excerpt: Majespecter with a bunch of draw engine/spellcaster good stuff
deck_description:
Majesty as Deck Master is very flexible - domains of Wind, Spellcaster, Majespecter, and Dracoslayer. Supercell gives Majespecter a great resource engine, and Yamarashi being quick summon from hand (and re-setting Wind) means you can keep fuelling your Kirin bounce and backrow tributes throughout each of your opponents' turns. The most effective way to play this is probably a form of "protect the castle", with the castle being Secret Village, unfortunately - Kirin bounce and monster removal from the Majespecter backrow helping keep spellcasters off of every board at once, hopefully.

Using the normal summon on a card draw engine (Blue Boy into Knowledge, any spellcaster including Majesty normalled from DM zone into Artemis into Wonder Wand, etc) is fine, because Majesty scale alongside any other Majespecter or Dracoslayer name is potential full combo;

Majesty search Dinomight Powerload, pop the other scale, scale Dinomight summon Majesty, Majesty search Majesty's Pegasus, Pegasus tribute Majesty for Bunbuku, Bunbuku search Yamarashi, Majesty back to DM zone, summon Yamarashi, link into Nue, Nue put Yata and Kyubi onto extra, scale Majesty from DM zone again, pend the Yata, Kyubi, and Bunbuku, search Wind and Tempest, overlay Yata and Kyubi for Paladin, set both and search a pend (like Luster Pendulum) with Paladin is minimum combo, with Wind being able to tribute Bunbuku summon Kirin from deck, and then Yamarashi able to summon itself, re-set Wind, and then act as a recurring summon for Kirin.

Gets a hell of a lot better if able to search for Secret Village instead of Majesty's, ofc.

deck_excerpt: Ever want to +7 for no reason? Well I got a deck for you!
deck_description:
Hey Duelist! It's ya boi, UltraGamerSoul, I'm back from the dead! Ooooo~

Jokes aside, I know people are mostly here for the decklist, but I gotta say something before we go on. It's been a while and even though I've been on and off, I'm thinking about doing more decklists for the future. Will they be consistent in upload schedule? Hell would I know. But, it would be very much appreciated if ya'll (if you want to) follow me (if that is possible, I dont know if it is [That's how you know its been a while since I've been on this site RIP] but oh well) for anymore decklists or just wanting some fun stuff. Either way, I appreciate all of you for viewing my decklist and can't wait to do some more!

Time for what the deck does!... Do I really need to explain what the deck does or can we skip this? All jokes. Runick Spright Fur Hire (that sure is a long ass deck name, for now, we'll call it R.S.FH. for now) is all about using Fur Hires for an actual use now by using the Runick engine to gain tons of advantage and draws, while having great disruptions and having a small Spright package to extend plays and whatnot. R.S.FH. is a bit complicated if you don't know what you're doing, but once you see what you need to do, anyone can pick this deck up! Even baby foxes! Anyway, think of these decks as just an easy way to plus off of 2 cards, Fountain and Folgo. Fountain allowing you to draw 3 as long as you have 3 Runick Spells in the GY and Foldo drawing you 3 if you control 3 Fur Hire monsters once an opponent's monster is destroyed by battle or effects. This deck has some pretty easy combos and can easily allow you to, on occasions, +7, which is wack, but oh boy is it fun!

For anyone wondering what's different about my deck, is the fact that I decided to put a second Jet and Starter on side for any Game 2 or 3 determinative matches, 2 Nib's for any nasty Snake-Eyes deck, especially now with the Fiendsmith engine, ZEUS for any occasional XYZ that stayed on the field, and of course, Sleipnir, the main guy on the cover, he's mostly here for easy disruptions, also he looks cool, so I decided to put him here. You can easily change some ways this deck works, like changing the extra to have more links for link climbing, having more disrupts, or the occasional niche tech pick. I've been having fun with this version of the deck, so enjoy!

P.S. If this gets at least 10k views, I'll make a Pure Fur Hire decklist for all of ya'll, but only if this hits 10k, if it doesn't reach the goal, then I won't post the decklist. Probably for the best but who knows, maybe ya'll are interested in it?

Double P.S. if you are wondering about the 3 Ash's in the side, it's because I feel like putting it in side does best in a format where handtraps are good, but not needed, up until next game or so, in which you can side deck anything, henceforth why Nib is on side.

deck_description:
I think it's safe to say that I have a slight obsession with the Superheavy Samurai engine. Any deck I could potentially run it in, I try a build with it included. With the Exosisters being a Rank 4 deck, I thought I'd give it a try. This idea may sound dumb, given Martha locks you into Exosisters, but with the amount of monsters that get you into your Rank 4 plays, it more than makes up for it.

Of course, the deck is rocking the Spirit package of Sakitama and Aratama, but the packages don't stop there. Not only does the deck have Spirits and SHS, but I'm also running Zexal Field, which can take an already good opening hand and make a potential game ender for your opponent. Using the effect of Zexal Field when summoning Exosisters Magnifica allows you to hit your opponent with the Xyz equivalent of King Calamity, King Kali Yuga.

Even if you don't open Zexal Construction or Field, you're still playing Exosisters, which is a good deck on its own. With so many ways to go full combo to end on Magnifica+Returnia, on top of potential hand rips with Omega or back row disruption with Tornado Dragon, this is a deck that could hold it's own in the upcoming format.

deck_excerpt: The Yubel engine is the next evolution to the Branded strategy!
deck_description:
Nearly two years of Branded has existed in Masterduel, and we still get cool new ways to play the archetype! With the recent release of "Eternal Partners," we get Yubel archetype's powerups and it is an indirect buff to the Albaz and friends. In addition to the regular playstyle of Branded, Yubel can now be used as a monster negate engine - effectively granting the deck an extra 3 copies of Called by the Grave. The Yubel cards are fairly minimal and it is composed of 5 cards. It is comprised of 3 Nightmare Throne, 1 Spirit of Yubel and 1 OG Yubel. Upon activation, Nightmare Throne destroys in deck Spirit of Yubel, which floats into the OG Yubel from deck. From there, a Phantom of Yubel can be summoned, granting Branded another way to deal with handtraps like Ash Blossom! Phantom of Yubel grants a higher success rate for Branded Fusion to successfully resolve - thus winning you more games! 

Yubel can also break boards and bait handtraps, since most gamestates are monster interaction based nowadays, the opposing player will be forced to prematurely use their interruption in an effort to stop Phantom of Yubel from coming out! After Yubel has sufficiently used up your opponent's interruption, you can go for your regular Branded plays unimpeded, without fear of Ash Blossom or Nibiru! 
 
The Yubel cards also aren't really "bricks" since they can be discarded to the GY as part of your Branded combos. If you happen to have both Yubels in the GY (through Branded Fusion, Grass Grows Greener, etc.) you can also make Phantom of Yubel relatively free! 

While not entirely game changing and it doesn't largely change the strategy, the "Yubel engine" grants another layer of protection of Branded. I highly recommend my fellow Branded bros to try out this next evolution of Albaz and friends!
 
Also, if you want a proper guide and combos how to pilot Branded, check out my earlier guide by clicking here. 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: This is a thing that might work
deck_description: This is a thing that might work
whilst i was messing with this deck i thought "well, i don't use my normal summon, and i get at least 3 bodies on field in a turn... why not put obelisk in it, and see what happens amirite?

Strategy for Playing Joey Wheeler Meta Deck

  1. Opening Moves:

    • Use The Black Stone of Legend to quickly summon Red-Eyes Black Dragon from your deck.
    • If you have Red-Eyes Fusion in your hand, use it to summon a powerful fusion monster like Meteor Black Comet Dragon from your extra deck.

  2. Maintaining Field Presence:

    • Use Red-Eyes Spirit and Return of the Red-Eyes to revive Red-Eyes monsters from the graveyard.
    • Utilize Red-Eyes Fang with Chain to enhance your Red-Eyes monster and steal your opponent's monsters.

  3. Controlling the Game:

    • Summon Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon to put pressure on your opponent each time they activate a card or effect.
    • Use Solemn Strike and Solemn Warning to negate key summons and effects from your opponent.

  4. Resource Management:

    • Utilize Red-Eyes Wyvern to summon Red-Eyes monsters from the graveyard at the end of the turn if you haven't conducted your normal summon.
    • Use Black Metal Dragon to boost the ATK of Red-Eyes monsters and search for Red-Eyes cards from your deck when sent to the graveyard.

  5. Finishing Moves:

    • Use Inferno Fire Blast to deal direct damage to your opponent using Red-Eyes Black Dragon.
    • Summon Borreload Dragon and Borrelsword Dragon for powerful finishing attacks and field control.

Strategy for Playing Seto Kaiba Meta Deck

  1. Opening Moves:

    • Use The White Stone of Ancients and Sage with Eyes of Blue to quickly summon Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your deck.
    • If you have The Melody of Awakening Dragon in your hand, use it to search for Blue-Eyes White Dragon and Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon.

  2. Maintaining Field Presence:

    • Use Dragon Spirit of White to banish your opponent's Spell/Trap cards when it is summoned.
    • Utilize Return of the Dragon Lords to protect your Dragon monsters from being destroyed by battle or card effects.

  3. Controlling the Game:

    • Summon Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon to negate graveyard effects and summon other Synchro Dragons during your opponent's turn.
    • Use Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon to revive Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your graveyard and provide protection for your Dragons.

  4. Resource Management:

    • Utilize The White Stone of Ancients to retrieve Blue-Eyes White Dragon from the graveyard during the End Phase.
    • Use Trade-In and Cards of Consonance to draw additional cards and increase the consistency of your deck.

  5. Finishing Moves:

    • Summon Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy to negate your opponent's Spell cards and redirect attacks.
    • Utilize Galaxy-Eyes Dark Matter Dragon for powerful attacks and to send Dragon monsters from your deck to the graveyard for future plays.

Strategy for Playing Mai Valentine Meta Deck

  1. Opening Moves:

    • Use Harpie Channeler to quickly summon Harpie Lady or Harpie Pet Dragon from your deck.
    • If you have Hysteric Sign in your hand, activate it to search for key Harpie cards like Elegant Egotist or Harpie's Hunting Ground.

  2. Maintaining Field Presence:

    • Use Harpie Harpist to search for additional Harpie monsters when it is sent to the graveyard.
    • Activate Harpie's Hunting Ground to destroy your opponent's Spell/Trap cards whenever a Harpie monster is summoned.

  3. Controlling the Game:

    • Summon Cyber Slash Harpie Lady to bounce your opponent's monsters back to their hand whenever you activate a Spell/Trap card.
    • Use Harpy's Feather Storm to negate your opponent's monster effects during the turn, gaining a significant advantage.

  4. Resource Management:

    • Utilize Hysteric Sign to add multiple Harpie cards from your deck to your hand during the End Phase.
    • Use Swallow's Nest to swap out your Harpie monsters for others, triggering their effects and maintaining a strong field presence.

  5. Finishing Moves:

    • Summon Number 11: Big Eye to take control of your opponent's monsters.
    • Use Lightning Chidori to send your opponent's set cards back to the deck and gain field control.
    • Summon Ice Beast Zerofyne to negate the effects of all face-up cards your opponent controls, then gain ATK for each face-up card on the field.

deck_excerpt: 17 Centur-Ion cards then 23 cards that help.
deck_description:
The deck's primary line is pretty simple.

Start with either Centur-Ion Primera, Centur-Ion Trudea. Stand Up Centur-Ion!, Bonfire, or Emblema Oath.

 

IF you have Centur-Ion Primera:

- Normal summon Centur-Ion Primera and activate its effect to add Stand Up Centur-Ion! to hand.

- Activate Stand Up Centur-Ion and activate its effect to discard a card and place Centur-Ion Trudea in your Spell/Trap zone.

- Activate Centur-Ion Trudea's effect to special summon it, then activate its effect again to return it to your Spell/Trap zone and add Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to your Spell/Trap zone.

- Activate Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to special summon it but DO NOT decrease its level by 4.

- Tune Centur-Ion Primera with Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to make Centur-Ion Auxila.

- Activate Centur-Ion Auxila's effect to add Centur-Ion Emeth VI to hand.

 

IF you have Centur-Ion Trudea or Bonfire:

- Activate Bonfire to add Centur-Ion Trudea to hand (Skip if you already have Trudea).

- Normal Summon Centur-Ion Trudea and use its effect to place it in your Spell/Trap zone alongside Centur-Ion Primera.

- Activate Centur-Ion Primera's effect to special summon it and add Stand Up Centur-Ion! to your hand.

- Activate Stand Up Centur-Ion! to discard a card and place Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to your Spell/Trap zone.

- Activate Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to special summon it but DO NOT decrease its level by 4.

- Tune Centur-Ion Primera with Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to make Centur-Ion Auxila.

- Activate Centur-Ion Auxila's effect to add Centur-Ion Emeth VI to hand.

 

IF you have Stand Up Centur-Ion! or Emblema Oath:

- Activate Emblema Oath to set Stand Up Centur-Ion! (Skip if you already have Stand Up Centur-Ion!).

- Activate Stand Up Centur-Ion, discard a card, and place Centur-Ion Primera in your Spell/Trap zone.

- Activate Centur-Ion Primera to special summon it and add Centur-Ion Trudea to your hand.

- Normal summon Centur-Ion Trudea and use its effect to place it in your Spell/Trap zone alongside Centur-Ion Gargoyle II.

- Activate Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to special summon it but DO NOT decrease its level by 4.

- Tune Centur-Ion Primera with Centur-Ion Gargoyle II to make Centur-Ion Auxila.

- Activate Centur-Ion Auxila's effect to add Centur-Ion Emeth VI to hand.

This is the closest you can get with fair to play cards, to simulate a Paradox borthers deck profile for Legacy of the Duelist: Link Evolution.

Otherwise, you need a deck with DRAW-POWER + "painful choice" + "soul charge" to summon the GOAT "Gate Guardian" and protect it with cards like "safe zone", "dimension guardian" or "power of the guardians". But it feels pretty unfair IMO!

Other ways of building a Gate Guardian deck profile is by using:

a) Pendulums (something that I don't really like), to special summon as many Kazejin, Suijin, Sanga as possible from hand.

b) "Mausoleum of the emperor", or with the help of cards like "Lightning Vortex" + "Twin Twisters" by discarding the level 7 monsters and then bringing them back from grave.

c) extreme stun + Draw (pot of greed x3)

d) steal opponent's monsters and tributing them with "crackdown" + "the monarchs stormforth" for example.

Strategy for Playing Rex Raptor Meta Deck

  1. Opening Moves:

    • Use Fossil Dig to search for key Dinosaur monsters like Soul-Eating Oviraptor or Babycerasaurus.
    • Activate Lost World to disrupt your opponent's plays and protect your Dinosaurs.

  2. Maintaining Field Presence:

    • Use Soul-Eating Oviraptor to search for Dinosaur monsters or send them to the graveyard to set up for future plays.
    • Summon Miscellaneousaurus to protect your Dinosaurs from opponent's effects.

  3. Controlling the Game:

    • Summon Ultimate Tyranno for a powerful offensive presence.
    • Use Survival's End to destroy Dinosaur monsters and disrupt your opponent's field.

  4. Resource Management:

    • Utilize Petiteranodon and Babycerasaurus to summon more powerful Dinosaur monsters when they are destroyed.
    • Use Double Evolution Pill to special summon powerful Dinosaur monsters from your hand or deck.

  5. Finishing Moves:

    • Summon Evolzar Laggia or Evolzar Dolkka to negate your opponent's plays and establish board control.
    • Utilize Accesscode Talker and Borrelsword Dragon for powerful finishing attacks and OTK (One Turn Kill) potential.

Strategy for Playing Weevil Underwood Meta Deck

  1. Opening Moves:

    • Use Insect Imitation to quickly summon higher level Insect monsters from your deck.
    • Activate Verdant Sanctuary to search for more Insect monsters whenever they are sent to the graveyard.

  2. Maintaining Field Presence:

    • Use Gokipole to search for powerful Insect monsters and destroy your opponent's face-up cards when it is sent to the graveyard.
    • Summon Inzektor Dragonfly and equip it with Inzektor Hornet to destroy your opponent's cards and trigger additional summons.

  3. Controlling the Game:

    • Summon Inzektor Picofalena to equip Insect monsters from your deck to other Insect monsters, enabling powerful combo plays.
    • Use Number 3: Cicada King to negate your opponent's monster effects and maintain control over the field.

  4. Resource Management:

    • Utilize Resonance Insect to search for high-level Insect monsters when it is sent to the graveyard.
    • Use Foolish Burial to send key Insect monsters to the graveyard for later revival with Monster Reborn.

  5. Finishing Moves:

    • Summon Accesscode Talker for a powerful finishing move by linking into it with multiple Insect monsters.
    • Utilize Inzektor Exa-Beetle to equip and send cards to the graveyard, disrupting your opponent's plays and establishing a strong board presence.

Strategy for Playing Yami Bakura Meta Deck

  1. Opening Moves:

    • Use Tour Guide From the Underworld to quickly summon a Level 3 Fiend from your deck, enabling Rank 3 XYZ plays.
    • Utilize Foolish Burial and Armageddon Knight to send Fiend monsters to the graveyard, setting up plays for Dark Necrofear and Destiny HERO - Plasma.

  2. Maintaining Field Presence:

    • Summon Fiendish Rhino Warrior to protect your Fiend monsters from being destroyed by battle or card effects and send additional Fiends to the graveyard when it is sent there.
    • Activate Dark Sanctuary to disrupt your opponent's attacks and inflict damage back to them.

  3. Controlling the Game:

    • Summon Dark Necrofear by banishing three Fiend monsters from your graveyard to gain control of your opponent's monster when it is destroyed.
    • Use Destiny HERO - Plasma to negate your opponent's monster effects and gain control of one of their monsters.

  4. Resource Management:

    • Utilize Resonance Insect to search for high-level Insect monsters when it is sent to the graveyard.
    • Use Necroface to recycle banished cards back into the deck, maintaining your resources.

  5. Finishing Moves:

    • Summon Accesscode Talker for powerful finishing moves by linking into it with multiple Fiend monsters.
    • Utilize Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy to negate your opponent's Spell cards and redirect attacks.

i dont want to put anything here

Note this is if Red Rose Dragon was at 3 in the TCG. There is really no reason for it be limited now.

I tried to get Rose Dragon to a point where it could be played in smaller settings.

Blue Rose Dragon is played because it is a non-tunner that can be searched with Roxrose Dragon, and it can be special summoned with White Rose Cluster and Basal Rose Shoot.

Ruddy Rose Witch is played due to the ability to bring back Black Rose Dragon or Ruddy Rose Dragon from the graveyard or banished. It is played without Witch of the Black Rose and Rose Fairy because those two cards are bricks that you never want to draw and the reward for playing them is only a plus one. Also witch is a level 4 tunner and fairy is a level 3 non-tunner which is the reverse of the most of the all monsters so you really don't want to draw them.

The extra deck is very tight which is why there is not more copies of Black Rose Dragon and Ruddy Rose Dragon. Also it is the reason for the need to play Ruddy Rose Witch for the grind game.

Some board breakers and/or hand traps would help the deck, but you would also have a harder time getting started so I left them out.

I am open to ideas on how to improve the deck while also still being true to the core of the deck.

deck_name: Beginner's Guide to White Forest Runick (July 2024)
deck_excerpt: White Forest is MADE to be played with Runick! The synergy is too perfect!
deck_description:
Seeing for the first time the archetype of "White Forest" in the newest set Infinite Forbidden, I immediately thought about their potential applications to Runick since it seems like both archetypes synergize well with each other! White Woods interacts with spells, draws additional cards, and easily facilitates synchro summons due their ability to spam out tuners. Meanwhile Runick adds additional draw power, extra synchro bodies, and adaptability due to their toolbox quick-play spells. These two were made for each other! Thus a new Runick variant was born (MAN I LOVE RUNICK)!
 
Rciela turns enables a search for any White Forest card for a low cost of a spell/trap discard, further fueling your GY with Runick spells. Silvera acts as a quick-play "book of the eclipse" setting facedown your opponent's entire field. Finally, Diabell recovers ANY spell/trap from the GY, while enabling a quick synchro during your opponent's turn! 

These white forest girls mean business, since they make synchro plays ridiculously easy whenever and wherever they are played. The amount of card advantage both strategies generate outpace most decks of the format in a prolonged grindgame, easily winning duels with a myriad of synchro-based interruptions. Diabellestar's "synchro" archetype certainly shows a lot of promise as a synchro engine - especially when it's paired up with a defensive powerhouse like Runick! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
White Forest Runick is made up of two different archetypes and one support engine. 

The WHITE FOREST section of the strategy are synchro-enablers, allowing the pilot to summon multiple synchro boss monsters to the field. White Forest cards also synergize very well with spell cards, since they use them as cost to enable them to spam tuners and synchro material on the field. The starters are 3 Astellar, 2 Elzette and 3 Silvy - all searchers and summoners from deck. 1 Rucia used as a searchable extender of the deck. 3 Tales of the White Forest (searcher), 1 Beware of the White Forest (target destroy), and 1 Woes of the White Forest (interruption) are used since they all reset themselves on the field when they are sent to the GY as cost for a monster effect, perfect to sending to the GY with Runick Hugin. 
 
A TOY BOX engine is used to further fuel the White Forest portion of the deck. Toy Box and Toy Soldier search each other, and Toy Box sets two cards from deck - giving White Forest plenty of spells to send to the GY as cost. The Toy Box monsters also summon themselves to the field whenever they're sent to the GY, so it gives additional bodies for synchro summons! Finally, Toy Box has a surprise battle phase effect to destroy attacking monsters by sending a set card to the GY, offering further defensive play. It is composed of 2 Toy Box, 2 Toy Soldier and 1 Toy Tank. 
 
RUNICK offers an alternative win condition of this deck by banishing your opponent's deck. Runick also increases the deck's consistency and grindgame since it allows for a draw 1-3 per turn. The Extra Deck Runick monsters such as Hugin and Geri are perfect synchro material, serving as level 2 and level 4 bodies. The Runick Extra Deck monsters are used at 1 each, since only 1 of each is generally needed per duel and the Extra Deck is super tight since it needs space for Synchro monsters. 
 
Contrary to other decks, White Forest Runick has only 1 STAPLE card which is Called By the Grave. Since it's all "engine" cards, White Forest Runick has a lot of gas and can generally play through 1-2 interruptions, especially when the Toy Box engine is involved. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of White Forest Runick is to control/banish your opponent's resources until they surrender or deck-out. The strategy also generates a lot of ATK on board so the duelist can potentially attack for game! This strategy interrupts your opponent with Silvera's fieldwide "Book of Eclipse," Chengying's banish, and Diabell's quick-synchro into Chaos Angel's banish. That is in addition to drawing 3-4 cards (which are potentially Runick quick-play spell interruptions) per turn with the Runick Fountain!
 
White Forest Runick combos are somewhat linear. They consist of climbing to Synchro 6s -> 8s -> 10s and potentially 12s as the combo goes on. Depending on your hand, White Forest Runick duelists end on a mix of Chengying (banish), Dis Pater/Crystal Wing (negate + destroy), Diabelle (quick synchro), Silvera (set opponent's entire field) and several Runick spells in hand. These boards are generally enough to stop an opponent's turn and outresource them with both White Woods and Runick! 
 
Here is the optimal opening combo for White Forest Runick: 
 
Any Runick Quick-Play Spell + Astellar + Toy Box + Any Discard = Diabell (Quick synchro -> Chaos Angel's banish/protection), Chengying (banish), Woes of the White Forest (Quick synchro -> Silvera's set of your opponent's board), 2-4 Runick spells in hand with Fountain, Draw 2 (Rucia and Tri-Edge both draw 1), follow-up for next turn in hand and GY. 
  1. During draw phase, (to play around Droll/Veiler) activate your Runick quick-play spell to special summon Hugin from your Extra Deck. 
  2. Activate Hugin's effect to discard any card from hand to search for Runick Fountain. 
  3. Enter Main Phase. Activate Toy Box and set from deck Toy Soldier and Toy Tank. 
  4. Normal summon Astellar. Activate Astellar's effect sending your set Toy Soldier to GY to summon Silvy from deck.
  5. CL1 Silvy's effect to search for Elzette, CL2 Toy Soldier's effect to summon itself from GY. 
  6. Activate Toy Soldier's effect on field to search for a level 4 light from deck, that being Rucia. 
  7. Synchro summon Rciela using Silvy + Hugin. 
  8. Activate Rciela's effect on-summon sending your set Toy Tank to search from deck Woes of the White Forest. 
  9. CL1 activate Astellar's trigger effect to summon herself from GY, Cl2 Toy Tank's effect to summon itself from GY. 
  10. Activate Elzette's effect to summon herself from hand sending Woes of the White Forest to GY and adding any White Forest monster from deck to hand (follow-up for next turn). 
  11. Activate Woes of the White Forest's GY effect to set itself on the field when sent to GY. 
  12. Special summon Rucia from hand. Activate Rucia's effect sending Toy Box the GY to draw 1 card. 
  13. Synchro summon Diabell using Rciela + Elzette. 
  14. Activate Diabell's on-summon effect to re-add your any spell/trap from your GY to hand (this is optional, but if you have an extra spell/trap, do it!)
  15. Synchro summon Crimson Dragon using Rucia + Toy Tank + Toy Soldier.
  16. Activate Crimson Dragon's effect add Synchro Rumble from deck to hand. 
  17. Activate Crimson Dragon's effect targeting Diabell so it can return itself to synchro summon Crystal Wing from your Extra Deck. 
  18. Activate Either Rucia or Silvy's effect in the GY to return Rciela to the Extra Deck to summon themselves from the GY. 
  19. Synchro summon Tri-Edge Master using Rucia/Silvy + Astellar. Draw 1 card with Tri-Edge Master's effect. 
  20. Activate Synchro Rumble to summon from GY Rucia/Silvy. Synchro summon Chengying using Tri-Edge Master + Rucia/Silvy. 
  21. Activate Runick Fountain. If you have any other Runick spells, activate them so you can possibly extend your Synchro plays and draw 1-3 cards. 
  22. During your opponent's turn, quick synchro with Diabell for Chao Angel's banish/protection. Afterwards, you can summon from GY Rucia/Silvy by shuffling back your Diabell, then activate Woes of the White Forest to quick-synchro into Silvera to set your opponent's entire field face-down. All these synchro plays recur your White Woods engine from the GY (Astellar resummons herself and Elzette adds herself back to hand). In addition, you can banish your opponent's cards with Chengying and interrupt them with your Runick quick-play spells!
For your next turn, your additional draws and White Woods recursion should allow you to out-resource your opponent! 
 
Obviously due to the mass amount of handtraps in this format you aren't always going to achieve this board and gamestate. This strategy can shrug off low impact handtraps like Ash, Imperm and Veiler but cards like Droll/Shifter almost always completely end your turn. Hands always differ as well, leading to different endboards - but generally it consists of several synchro boss monsters with Runick Fountain + spells. 
 
Going second, you pray you can break your opponent's board with Runick spells + the natural amount of gas that White Forest has with Toy Box. Otherwise, when siding for second, side out your entire Toy Box engine (5 cards) along with Woes of the White Woods, Beware the White Woods and Synchro Rumble for an additional 8 boardbreakers from your Side Deck. Decks generally don't have a spell/trap negate or you can bait the negate with a Flashing Fire or a Freezing Curses, then break the board wide open with a Lightning Storm of a Evenly Matched. From there, you can play your White Forest Runick as normal. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • The Extra Deck is really tight! If you want more space take out the Crimson Dragon package including Crystal Wing and Dis Pater from the Extra Deck and Synchro Rumble from the Main Deck. Potential cards to add to the Extra Deck are additional Runick monsters, TY-Phon, Bagooska and Daigusto Emeral. 
  • If you want more space in the Main Deck for staples, take out Synchro Rumble, and the 5 Toy Box cards from the Main Deck. 
  • When you summon Hugin, always try to discard a White Woods spell/trap since they reset themselves from the GY if discarded as cost for a monster effect. 
  • To break your opponent's board as you go through your synchro combo, summon Silvera (sets every monster of your opponent's facedown), Coral Dragon (destroy 1), Chengying (banish), S:P Little Knight (banish), and Sleipnir (banish). This is in addition to any Runick spells you have! 
  • White Forest Runick generates a surprising amount of attack on the board. You can potentially attack for game by controlling your opponent to a standstill, and purposefully not using a Runick spell so you can attack! 
  • Every turn, be sure to enter Battle Phase so that it's automatically skipped so you can potentially attack your next turn.
  • The cards you side out for your Side Deck in games 2-3 are the Toy Box Engine, Synchro Rumble, Woe/Beware the White Woods and Runick Dispelling/Smiting Storm. 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
As a seasoned Runick duelist, I was pleasantly surprised when I saw that the White Forest cards synergize extremely well with the strategy! While Runick provides extra synchro bodies, draws, consistency and fuel, the White Forest cards raise the power ceiling by spamming out tuners to enable massive Synchro bosses! The recursion that both decks have will most definitely outresource your opponent in a prolonged grindgame. Not only are these forest ladies beautifully aesthetic, they are dangerously lethal synchro powerhouse when combined with Runick. 
 
GLHF Duelists!

Placement: Top 32

I have been really enjoying playing mimighoul it's a really good first wave for the TCG. The deck does lack a solid turn 0 board but can keep up grind games with most meta decks and creates some really fun and interesting simplified gamestates. The deck has to play a supporting engine at the moment with its current release is the only issue with it as it does not set up meaniful enough boards. The mimighoul board turn 0 without the field spell and the trap in hand is just watching your opponent flip archfiend/ cerburus up and that being all the interaction on board/ relying on hand traps. This is also the reason why mimighoul gets to play the fun and fair card that is shifter, in it's current state the deck is draw the kashtira engine, droll or shifter and hope that's enough to get through first turn to begin the grind game.

The deck can grind basically every deck in the meta apart from snake-eyes if they open well and the horus engine is an issue as well if you can't access zeus because they keep putting big bodies on the field to deal with which is a pain as mimighoul has no spell or trap card removal in archetype to stop this. This deck also has a really good match up vs tenpai which is very funny that deck struggles against the mimighoul board because of how painful the field spell is for them and that the trap does not allow them to otk alongside the field spell. 

I have seen other builds using guard dog and other flip monsters to cheese out wins and handrips but with maker being random I'd rather just use put more hand traps in the deck or consistency cards to instead have more interaction that is always avaliavle and not reliant on a coin flip. I have also seen builds maining/ siding summoning curse but in practise I have preferred D.D.G as it's another copy of shifter which most decks can't play through and if they set up a board loosing advantage this deck will always win that grind game because the field spell is so good. 

The side deck is built around this current format, mimighoul struggles to get bodys on board going second so siding bystials, Phantazmay and nibiru is all about creating board presense to force interaction on the current threats on board rather then what will be played once the cards on field have been used.

deck_excerpt: Fiendsmith Yubel  / North America WCQ 2024 Top 64
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Bryan Pham

Tournament: North America WCQ 2024 – July 19th 2024

Placement: Top 64

this deck can do some very cool stuff like for example dealing up to 32k damage (without using prosperity)

another cool thing it can do is that it can play around shifter and even otk through it

thirdly: THIS DECK CAN OTK UNDER PROSPERITY 

fourth : it is pretty budget (compared to fiendsmith snake eyes

also if you get d barried on synchros you can otk through the link otk with princess and zealantis

Start With Eyes of Magic

The Goal of this Deck is to use the "With Eyes of Blue" cards to it's maximum to gain advantage. These cards focus on targeting your own Monsters to gain further advantage. You will also shuffle Blue-Eyes White Dragon into your Deck often to be able to keep using your mill effects which makes Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon a no go for this strategy. But were do we even Start? Let's take a look at the LV1 tuner Monsters.

If you or the opponent targets Priestess with Eyes of Blue she can send an effect Monster to the GY to search any 2 Blue-Eyes Monsters from your Deck. Normally you search the OG Blue-Eyes White Dragon and Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon. Like that you already have one Blue-Eyes Monster on your field quickly. In a following turn you can shuffle a Blue-Eyes Monster from the field into the Deck to resummon her from the GY. This 2nd effect doesn't come up very often since she can only use 1 effect per turn. It does have very nice Combo Potential with Blue-Eyes Solid Dragonwhich I will explain further below.

Maiden with Eyes of Blue is the other Monster which wants to be targeted by Card effects or by an attack. If that happens you can summon one Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your Hand, Deck or GY without any cost. If the opponent attacks her she also changes her Battle Position on top of the summon effect. So how do we target these 2? 

Protector with Eyes of Blue is one of many options to achieve that. When you normal summon him you can special a LV1 Light Tuner from your Hand. And you can also target one of your effect Monsters, send it to the GY and special summon one Blue-Eyes Monster from your Hand. He's especially nice to follow up with Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon since you can easily keep field Advantage with him. 

Master with Eyes of Blue is similar. On normal summon you can return a LV1 Light Tuner from your GY back to the Hand. If he's in the GY you can shuffle him back into the Deck, then target one effect Monster and send it to the GY and then summon any Blue-Eyes Monster from your GY other then the sent Monster. 

Finally Sage with Eyes of Blue can on normal summon search any LV1 Light tuner from Deck to Hand. Even better is it, to discard him from your hand to target and send one effect Monster to the GY and then summon any Blue-Eyes Monster from the Deck.

All these effects are a "and if you do" type of effect, so be sure to not target the same Monster twice for sending or you won't get both effects. 

So these 5 Monsters already offer a great starting point but that's not all. This Deck has many starting points which you can combine in one form or another. Majesty with Eyes of Blue sounds strange but it does target and mill any Blue-Eyes Monster from the Hand or Deck to the GY. And as a quick play spell it can also be used to interrupt the opponents attack if necessary. It does prevent the targeted Monster from attacking permanently after all. 

Vision with Eyes of Blue is a newer "With Eyes of Blue" card which really helps out a lot. It easily specials any Monster you desire from your hand and can target and return to hand your Monsters too, activating the Priestess and Maids effect in the Process. It can help out a lot in setting up your Board every turn as long as you have cards in your Hand. Also you can only activate this card once per turn but the effect itself is a soft once per turn. If you manage to have multiple Copies of this card active you unlock some serious loop Potential with Dragon Spirit of White and Blue-Eyes Solid Dragon.

Be sure to use Bingo Machine, Go!!! to easily search for Vision with Eyes of Blue or your very useful Fusion Spell Ultimate Fusion or one of your Blue Eyes Monsters. A pretty versatile card which can help out a lot. 

The field Spell Mausoleum of White is even more useful since it enables an additional Normal Summon for a LV1 Light Tuner and can target them or any other Monster from you by milling one Normal Monster from the Hand or Deck. That will also give a nice 800 ATK/DEF Boost to the targeted Monster. You can also banish this card from the GY to search your in archetype Raigeki in the form of Burst Stream of Destruction (Could also be searched with a 33% Chance with Bingo Machine, Go!!!). The Mill effect is yet another Soft once per Turn so feel free to activate 2 Copies of this card in one turn and mill again. Combining this card with Beacon of White is also deadly since you can easily get an 3800 ATK Blue-Eyes White Dragononto the field which attacks at least 2+ times. (From my experience it's 5 to 6 attacks normally). 

All in all getting started is quite easy within this Deck. Next up how about some payoffs? 

 

Continue With Eyes of Victory 

Your go to Bossmonster most of the time will be Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon. With him you get 3000 DEF Wall which prevents the Special Summon of 2 or more Monsters at once, can negate a effect which activates in the GY and can tribute himself anytime to get out Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon from the Extra Deck. That guy is yet another 3000 DEF Wall which prevents targeting and destruction of Dragons you currently control until the end of the next turn. During your Standby Phase he can revive a Normal Monster from your GY too including Dragon Spirit of White.

These 2 Synchro bosses form the Base ressource loop of your Deck. By far not unbreakable but also quite formidable to this day. From this point you go into your 2 Main Board Breaker Bosses. 

Blue-Eyes Twin Burst Dragon can attack up to 2 Monsters with 3000 ATK and can't be destroyed by Battle. Any Monster he Attacks which is not destroyed by that Battle will be Banished after Damage Step. This is finest non targeting Removal to get over pretty much everything. 

Thunder End Dragon is the other 3000 ATK threat. By detaching 1 XYZ Material you can destroy all other Monsters on the field. Thanks to Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon your Dragon Monsters won't be harmed by that effect opening up an easy OTK line with Beacon of White after that. 

 

The Eyes of many Options

Unlike many other Blue-Eyes variants you play quite a few options in here to spice things up. Let's start with the Monsters. Blue-Eyes Solid Dragon is a rather unusual choice especially in an day an age were Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon exists. He turns out to be the perfect option to be summoned from anywhere. On summon he can negate the effects of one of the opponents Monsters permanently. If the opponent activates anything you can shuffle him back into the Deck to summon one Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your Deck instead. Perfect since Priestess with Eyes of Blue can keep shuffling the summoned Blue-Eyes back into the Deck with her GY effect and as for example Sage with Eyes of Blue can keep summoning the Solid Dragon back from the Deck after that. This is a quite easy to achieve loop that threatens 5500 Damage every turn with a Monster negate on top of it. Also if he's in the Hand and you have Vision with Eyes of Blue active twice you can loop this nasty Dragon every turn. He's a answer to many problems this Deck would otherwise have and for that I like him. 

Dragon Spirit of White is simple. He banishes on summon 1 Spell or Trap from the opponent and can tribute himself to special one Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your Hand. Since he's being treated as a Normal Monster Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon can keep summoning him back from the GY thus forming another loop in this Deck. With Vision with Eyes of Blue you can use this effect even more often. 

There are 3 different Ultimate Dragons in your Extra Deck to choose from. All need Ultimate Fusion to be summoned in this deck which shuffles Blue-Eyes White Dragon back into the Deck in the process. The OG Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon is the strongest non effect Monster which exists in all of Yugioh. He makes up for the most optimal Beacon of White target possible. 

Blue-Eyes Alternative Ultimate Dragon is the best Tower option. He comes with built in Targeting and Destruction protection and can destroy up to 3 Cards the opponent controls but cannot attack the turn you use that effect. 

Neo Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon is the most interesting of the three. If he's the only Face Up card you control he can attack up to three times by milling Blue-Eyes Fusion Monsters from your Extra Deck. The reason you play him 3 times is his secondary effect. If a Blue-Eyes monster is targeted you can banish him from the GY to negate and destroy that card. With him alone you have an easy OTK line hiding in your Extra Deck. 

The earlier mentioned Beacon of White is another hidden treasure. It comes with a hefty bunch of downsides: Only 1 Beacon can be active, 3 Blue-Eyes Monsters have to be in the GY to activate it, the reborn Monsters effects are negated, only it can attack and if the Beacon leaves the field that Monster is banished. But there's one little detail not many know about this card. The revived Monster can attack a number of times equal to the amount of Blue-Eyes Monsters in your GY. And this is not just against Monsters but general. Imagine a 4500 ATK Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon which can attack 10+ times easily. A very dangerous card for sure. From my experience I can tell that this card is absolutely worth it. 

 

The Eyes of Problems

As good as all of it sounds your plays are quite limited into OTK lines only but in the right hands it's certainly better then your average Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon beatdown deck and looking at Master Duel you get swiftly to Platin League with it (Diamond is kinda a stretch with it). Non targeting removal does hurt this Deck a lot. You do have to replace Blue-Eyes Alternative Ultimate Dragon since he does not exist in Master Duel but something like Underworld Goddess of the Closed World is always nice to be played instead. 

You will sometimes find yourself in Situations with no Outs against certain Cards the opponent is using. A Blue-Eyes Deck wants to overwhelm the opponent with strong beaters and a good Monster ressource Loop but that's about it. Finest Kaiba Style Gameplay.

 

The Eyes of Final Words

This Deck is a bit unusual. I don't play the all stars of Blue-Eyes many other's use, since they are to easy to out and to Bricky in my eyes. This Deck is consistent and strong in this shape and form. Give it a try if you like pure Archetype Decks or if you like to play a more simple type of Deck. I do find myself having fun to simply beatdown the opponent with pure Strength sometimes. 

 

Final Rating: 

★★★★★★★ OTK Potential

★★★★☆☆☆ Defensive Tools

★★★☆☆☆☆ Control Options

★★★★★☆☆ Removal Options

★★★★★☆☆ Recovery/Recycling

★★★☆☆☆☆ Card Advantage

Overall Rating: ★★★★☆☆☆ 27/42★

 

 

With Eyes of Rules

Below I will list some not so obvious rulings about some of these cards: 

Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon: Revealing one Blue-Eyes White Dragon and Special summoning this card is not treated as an effect.

Master with Eyes of Blue: His 2nd effect resolves after he's been returned to the Deck which makes interacting with his effect more difficult. 

Blue-Eyes Twin Burst Dragon: You can send Face Down Blue-Eyes White Dragon's to the GY to special summon this card.

deck_excerpt: Fiendsmith Yubel  / North America WCQ 2024 Top 64
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Cole Lambert

Tournament: North America WCQ 2024 – July 19th 2024

Placement: Top 64

Dark Magician core cards are at 29-30. Its Albaz/Branded engine is at 5-7. Why? Its simple. The focus is getting DM on the field and/or getting his Fusions on the field. The goal is setting up a Dragon Knight stall board (consisting of Circle and Eternal Soul) so you can utilize your resources for the next turn while exploiting your opponent's and gaining knowledge of the cards they use or play with. 

Card analysis:

1. Magician Navigation searches for the most important cards of the deck: DM, Apprentice, Dark Illusion, and DMG. The core ratios are at 2 except Dark Illusion. You can replace Dark Illusion with Mahad since they are both at 1. With the Branded build, its better to go with Mahad instead. Your best cards to help you would be Apprentice and/or DMG for ATK boost, searching, or combos with cards such as Salvation and Combination when you use Navigation, also, Navigation can negate Spell/Trap Cards even while Dragon Knight is on the field. 

2. Secrets of Dark Magic is at 3 because you can chain while Rod gets targeted by cards such as Effect Veiler or Impermanence. Circle can make it add 1+, also, Branded can discard or you can Fusion summon furthermore using Branded. This MUST remain at 3. Also, you can disrupt your opponents board on their turn if you have no more options or resources by summoning Quintet or Chimera.

3. Illusion of Chaos does not need Preparation but it does need Branded Fusion to get rid of a extra card which can help your draw power with cards like Soul Servant.

4. Soul Servant searches your important cards such as DM, Rod, Timaeus, Circle, Eternal, Souls, etc. Its important to have at 3. 

5. Fusion Deployment at 1 and Branded Fusion at 3 has good synergy and can cause continuous combos in 1 turn. Fusion Deployment can be used for 1 card combo by using Cartesia or can help you with Piercing the Darkness by summoning DM to draw 1 card. Branded Fusion is 1.5 card combo that can setup your Dragon Knight board quicker and setup a potential draw 2 (draw 3 if you use Mahad instead of Dark Illusion). Since Branded locks you out Extra Deck already (except for Fusion Summoning), Deployment does not make much of a difference. You can ratio Deployment at 2 and Branded at 2. But its best to leave Deployment at 1 and Branded at 3. Branded can setup Navigation negate quicker while DM the Dragon Knight is on the field.

6. Allure of Darkness can aid your draw power and has synergy with Lubellion to unbanish your DARK monsters that you banished after you drawn 2 cards. You can keep Albaz in your GY while you can unbanish the other through Branded Fusion. You should also have it ratio'd at 2. You can replace it with Wonder Wand since players use Ash Blossom for Rod. If they Ash Blossom you, you can draw 2 cards by sending Rod to the GY by using Wonder Wand instead. The choice is up to whatever the player feels comfortable with between Allure or Wonder Wand. 

7. Piercing the Darkness can increase DM the Dragon Knight ATK so other monsters cannot destroy it by battle and also help you draw 1 card each turn you summon DM. 

8. Magicalized Fusion can summon an extra Dragoon in the late game and can summon Quintet to field wipe your opponent. 

9. Apprentice Illusion can help you beat boss monsters in battle such as Dragoon by giving your Spellcasters a 2000 ATK Boost. You easily destroy powerful cards like Dark Dragoon in battle just by sending Apprentice to the GY. 

Also remember the MAIN goal is to setup the Dragon Knight board, then wait until your next turn to summon heavy boss monsters after your opponent uses and wastes resources. Dark Magician was ALWAYS meant to be played This way with DM the Dragon Knight, Circle, and Eternal Soul so you come back stronger during your next turn. Hint: Magicians Rod has a recycling effect for a reason so you can get access to more cards to deal with your opponent in more ways to win your way to victory. The mistake DM players make is trying shotgun Dark Dragoon for a easy win. You will NOT ever win your duels this way. You can summon Dragoon your next turn so you can OTK your opponent more properly after having knowledge on their Deck and strategies. The card ratios for each monster and Spell/Trap are perfectly good going first or second. 

"But what about having handtraps?" Then this deck would fail with them in it so it does not matter, win or lose. 90% of the time your opponent runs out of cards to use by cramming in handtraps that make lose resources and run out of good cards to play with in their hand. But adding or changing any other cards thats on here, will ruin the deck. So dont consider it. DARK MAGICIAN BEST DECK!

deck_description: So, this Deck is Somewhat Fiendsmith Snake-Eye but nerfed. The End board is I:P, Azurune ,Wave high King Cesar and some amount of Handtraps (your playing a lot of those). Really Fun Deck but if you have the Fiendsmith cards you probably can play something better than this

Play 'Allure of Darkness' to strengthen your current hand, but, be careful not to suicide your whole hand.

There are two strategies to pursue, depending on the cards you have. The first strategic aim is to access 'Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon' though 'Red-Eyes Fusion'. All other times, the strategic priority is to Summon/Special Summon as many monsters to the field as possible, in order to access XYZ and Link monsters in the Extra Deck relevant to the situation. There are strict conditions imposed by 'Red-Eyes Fusion' on the turn it's played, and the player must strategize around this limitation to utilize the rhythm and speed of the deck effectively.

Use 'Red-Eyes Insight' to search 'Red-Eyes Fusion'. Another way of searching 'Red-Eyes Fusion' is to activate the Graveyard Effect of 'Red-Eyes Black Meteor Dragon', however, you cannot activate this effect on the same turn it was sent to the Graveyard, so this play requires some setup. Another method of searching 'Red-Eyes Fusion' is to bring 'Black Metal Dragon' onto the field, then use him to Link Summon 'Striker Dragon'. This will trigger the effect of 'Black Metal Dragon' allowing the player to search 'Red-Eyes Fusion'. You can also use this method to search and then summon 'Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon' by Banish Tributing 'Striker Dragon'.

For a secondary target for 'Red-Eyes Insight' search 'Return of the Red-Eyes' which helps flood the field with monsters. 'Return of the Red-Eyes' synergises extremely well with 'Piercing the Darkness' enabling the player to draw a card when they Summon a Normal Monster once per turn. For example: On your turn 'Return of the Red-Eyes' activates and Summons a Normal Monster from the Graveyard to the field, which triggers 'Piercing the Darkness' allowing you to draw a card. At the start of the opponent's turn, the process repeats.

When paying the discard cost for activating 'Red-Eyes Insight' or 'Red Eyes Black Meteor Dragon', aim to discard two copies of 'Red-Eyes Black Dragon' from the deck. Always leave at least one copy of 'Red-Eyes Black Dragon' in deck or hand to access a Fusion Summon through 'Red-Eyes Fusion'. You can use 'Return of the Red-Eyes' to bring any Normal Monster from the Graveyard back to the field.

If going for the Fusion Summon, a major weakness to beware is that 'Ash Blossom' can negate 'Red-Eyes Fusion' with a deadly lingering-effect. Since the effect of 'Red-Eyes Fusion' would be negated, and not the activation, the summoning restriction effect of 'Red-Eyes Fusion' still resolves, thus the player cannot summon anything else that turn. You can counter 'Ash Blossom' with 'Called by the Grave' should you be fortunate enough to have it in hand.

Fusions Monsters in the Extra Deck can also be accessed through 'Necro Fusion', but requires a bit of foresight, fortune and setup to get the intended monsters into the Graveyard first.

'Red-Eyes Soul' is an excellent hand/field-trap that allows the player to Special Summon a Red-Eyes monster (except itself) from the deck or hand. The effect is easy to trigger, only requiring your opponent Special Summon a monster. Summoning 'Red-Eyes Darkness Metal' using this method is a priority. 'Red-Eyes Darkness Metal' helps to flood the field during your main phase by Special Summoning one Dragon monster from the hand or Graveyard. 'Noctovision Dragon' chains nicely to the resolution of 'Red-Eyes Soul'.

For going second, 'Evenly Matched' is very useful. 'Bystial Magnahamut' is excellent going second, use it on the opponent's turn to add 'The Black Stone of Legend' to hand at the end of the opponent's turn and also get a Monster onto the field before your own turn.

For some back row destruction 'Dark Armed, The Dragon of Annihilation' can target and destroy front or back row, for the cost of banishing a card in your Graveyard. The effect can be used twice in one turn. 'Harpies Feather Duster' also helps. Consider cards in the Side Deck when facing spell and trap heavy decks.

Red-Eyes Black Dragon is a metaphor about the power of potential. This deck can be enjoyable to play and has a slight competitive edge. I would gauge its power at Tier 3. Some may even consider it Rogue.

At locals, this deck has seen success against:

[Kashtira]
[Eldlich] 
[Swordsoul] 
[Blue-Eyes]
[Ninjas]

Authors Notes: This is a competitive build for a suboptimal archetype intended for casual play. The Red-Eyes archetype is extremely weak. I do not recommend this deck or any other build of pure Red-Eyes for competitive play. You WILL lose the majority of match ups, even in the casual setting.

deck_name: Pure Chaos MAX - Master Duel - July 2024
deck_excerpt: Pure Chaos MAX - Master Duel - July 2024

deck_description:
(Side deck is still in consideration)

Slow control deck with two main win conditions: Exodia the Forbidden One and Accesscode Talker  and the second wincon feeding right into the first one.  


Main combos are: normal summon Tour Guide From the Underworld to special Sangan from deck then link into Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomyfor double search;  


Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy + summon or his effect to special from opponent's GY to link into Selene, Queen of the Master Magiciansbringing back Witch of the Black Forest then link into Accesscode Talker or Unchained Abomination for a search + a good boss monster.  


Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer is an awesome stall and interrupting tool and coupled with the many stall cards in the deck ( Waboku, Battle Fader, Threatening Roar, One Day of Peace. Evenly Matched  ) makes slowing the game down to a pace that you can use to prolong the game for your first win condition to be achievable and/or set up enough searchers to thin the deck and easily get what you need.  


DPE is wonderful alongside The Legendary Exodia Incarnate as it's immune to card effects (be careful since it's also immune to your own Waboku) so you can effectively pop a card for free by targeting it with DPE's effect.  


Instant Fusion + Millennium-Eyes Restrict is there as one-of combo protection and can be linked once you're done, working as an extender.  

Battle Fader can be searched by Sangan, Witch of the Black Forest and Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy but remember that doing so with the first two of them prevents you from actually using it during that turn.

Relinquished Anima + Wonder Wand can be a tricky little unexpected spot removal after using Battle Fader during your opponent's turn.

 


Potential cuts: Legion the Fiend Jester and White Elephant's Gift  - still not sure about these two, they often feel like a brick more than anything tbh.   Probably would be better if replaced by some kind of staple or handtrap.

deck_excerpt: Exosister Vaalmonica! The sisters train Selettrice to fight evil. (pure Vaalmonica tutorial included!)
deck_description:
Hi, I made a post on Reddit discussing pure Vaalmonica combo, you can check it out here. But frfom here, I'm assuming you know the basics of Vaalmonica combos.

Overview
It's basically a Vaalmonican engine that churns out some extra sisters, as a result. Moreover, Disarmonia and the Scales(yuor devil or angle) can trigger Martha's effect to Xyz Summon. Aside from that, both decks can function (somewhat) under a Shifter, which is a great handtrap for the GY meta.

Combo Lines : 
...and there were no combo lines! Vaalmonica is very interconnected and extends one way or another(it's more of a checklist on what you should have; read the reddit guide). But a few tickmarks you need are : 

  • 3 Demone Counters
  • Zebufera(Purple Link) onfield
  • Followed Rhythm (either set or in the GY)

Basically, the ideal combo line is...

  1. Set up scales with the Scales' effects. 
  2. NSumm. Selettrice, add Scelta (or Invitare/Disarmonia, if you have both).
  3. Scelta, adds Invitare --> Invitare adds Angello to hand; Demone to E.D. (You can set Scales with this, as well)
  4. Pend. any card you can Pend.
  5. Demone --> Scelta, adds Versare(if you don't have any other way to get 3 counters, otherwise grab Followed Rhythm)
  6. Use Exosister/Selettrice + Demone or Martha's trigger effect--> Xyz, Mikailis.
  7. Mikailis, adds Vadis.
  8. Link to Zebufera using Mikailis. Set Traps.

Without any Exosisters being pend. and only Demone was summoned, this amounts to 4 summons, and won't trigger Nibiru.
This leads to blanket protection with Zebufera, 1 - 3 uses of Followed Rhythm, and provided Vadis triggers: a banish via Mikailis, a negate via Gibrine (or GY lock w/ Kaspitell). As for the side deck, I added Chosen Melody since it's less impactful and can be added per ratios. The extra Agathakako- for consistency, and Droll + Evenly for more disruption(you can discard Evenly using Angello).

deck_description:
I started looking at this deck back in Feburary, but it was always a little weird to me. I like decks that are open ended and not necissarily archetype locked, this is that to a T.The branded cards are a sort of toolbox to make a more diverse endboard that can change per matchup, the bystials can interupt fiendsmith, and the acrhfiend can grab Simul archfiend and turn off decks like White Forest, Tenpai, Gimmick Puppet, and even Snake-eyes.

Obviously, cards like nightmare apprentice are great, Diabellze is a floodgate, but they are kinda too pricy for me, especially nightmare apprentice.

I am also looking into a melodius engine which is why it is in the side deck.

after much testing this is the way I plan to build my insect deck after the release of Rage of the Abiss, I hesitated whether to include the synchro 6 or 2 copies of the battlewasp wind plus the level 5, but in the end the 2nd copy never gets in the way and it is even necessary to use the wasp in case you start with wind in the initial hand, analogously to why I carry 2 copies of the ragnaraika trap. The only thing missing is the handtrap that I leave to the reader to choose which one and in what number it would be appropriate since I need to test to know how many copies can be taken without compromising the performance of the deck.

deck_description: If youre going second you can get lucky and get Raider's Knight on the field with Mothman, Snoww, Genta, Catalyzer or Chupacabra the turbo into Arc Rebellion Xyz Dragon for a nice turn 2 Defense. If youre going first just try to get as many Dark World and Dark/Fiend Monsters into your GY, then Summon either the Grapha Fusion (If you know your Opponent has crucial Effects to Combo break) or a strong Clorless the turn after to have a Great oneshot with up to 16.000 ATK, a field wipe and untargetability ready to crush any fun Deck. The Deck is fairly easy to Brick and definitely can't compete with the Meta, but thats not what i made it for anyways. Have Fun!
